            <div class="panel-body">
              <p>This project contains three main components, each with its own option on the website menu. The first component includes the design, development, and testing of an open source Arduino-based air quality sensors. The sensors were designed, developed and tested this summer by students at the <a href="http://www.umass.edu/">University of Massachusetts Amherst</a> in the <a href="http://people.umass.edu/~aerosollab/">Peltier Aerosol Lab</a> and deployed in the city of Springfield, Massachusetts, USA. Prior to the development of the Arduino air quality sensors, we also collected air quality data in Kathmandu, Nepal using a proprietary air quality measuring device.</p>
			  <p>The remaining two components summarize the studies of air quality in two very different city contexts: Kathmandu, Nepal and Springfield, Massachusetts, USA. Each case study provides a description of the urban context and the policy/management question, the collection of data using environmental air sensors, the mapping of spatio-temporal data on the Web World Wind platform, the analysis of the data collected, and concludes with next steps.  In both cases, we implement a visualization of the time series data using NASA Web World Wind and demonstrate its analysis.</p><br/><br/><br/></br>
